# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: george-w-bush
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] The **147th Attack Wing** is a unit of the Texas Air National Guard, stationed at Ellington Field Joint Reserve Base, Houston, Texas.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] The Wing would be transferred to the United States Air Force Air Combat Command if brought into federal service.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] The 111th Attack Squadron, assigned to the wing's 147th Operations Group, is a descendant organization of the World War I 111th Air Squadron, established on 14 August 1917.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] It was reformed on 29 June 1923, as the 111th Observation Squadron, and is one of the 29 original National Guard Observation Squadrons of the United States Army National Guard that were formed before World War II.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] The 147th Attack Wing, based at Ellington Field in Houston, Texas, flies combat support missions 24/7 via advanced satellite communications, providing surveillance, reconnaissance, and air support for US and Allied forces.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In conducting combat support sorties, the 147th Attack Wing provides leadership at all levels with critical real-time Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance (ISR) air-to-ground munitions, and strike capability.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] A collocated Air Support Operations Squadron provides terminal control for weapons employment in a close air support scenario integrating combat air and ground operations.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In 1957, the Texas Air National Guard 111th Fighter-Interceptor Squadron, stationed at Ellington Air Force Base near Houston, was authorized to expand to a group level under the 136th Air Defense Wing.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] On 1 July 1957, the National Guard Bureau extended federal recognition to the **147th Fighter Group** (Air Defense).
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] The 111th was reassigned from the 136th Fighter-Interceptor Group to the 147th, becoming the new group's flying squadron.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Support squadrons of the 147th were the group headquarters, 147th Material Squadron (maintenance and supply), 147th Combat Support Squadron, and the 147th USAF Dispensary.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Initially equipped with the North American F-86D Sabre, in June 1959 the squadron traded their F-86Ds for the upgraded F-86L Sabre.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In August 1960, the unit became one of the first to transition to the Convair F-102A Delta Dagger Mach 2 all-weather interceptor, and began a 24-hour alert to guard the Texas Gulf coast.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In August 1961, as part of an Air Defense Command reorganization, the group's assignment to 136th Air Defense Wing was terminated with 136th being transferred to Tactical Air Command.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] The 147th was directly assigned to the Texas Air National Guard, being operationally gained by the Air Defense Command 33rd Air Division.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] One pilot who flew TF/F-102As with the 111th was 1st Lt.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Bush, a future Governor of Texas and President of the United States.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Bush's military service began in 1968 when he enlisted in the Texas Air National Guard after graduating with a bachelor's degree in history from Yale University.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] After being accepted into the air national guard, Airman Basic Bush was selected to attend pilot training.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] His six weeks of basic training was completed at Lackland Air Force Base, Texas during July and August 1968.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Upon its completion, Bush was promoted to the officer's rank of second lieutenant required for pilot candidates.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] He spent the next year in flight school at Moody Air Force Base, Georgia from November 1968 to November 1969.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Bush then returned to Ellington Air Force Base, Texas to complete seven months of combat crew training on the F-102 from December 1969 to June 1970.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] This period included five weeks of training on the Lockheed T-33 T-Bird and 16 weeks aboard the TF-102 Delta Dagger two-seat trainer and finally the single-seat F-102A.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Bush graduated from the training program in June 1970.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Bush remained in the Texas ANG as a certified F-102 pilot who participated in frequent drills and alerts through April 1972.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Bush was honorably discharged from the Air National Guard in October 1973 at the rank of First Lieutenant.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] An ANG physical dated 15 May 1971 indicates that he had logged 625 flight hours by that time, and he ultimately completed 326 hours as pilot and 10 as co-pilot while serving with the 111th Fighter-Interceptor Squadron.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In May 1971, the 111th added F-101B/F Voodoos and became the RTU for the twin seat F-101F type, while continuing as the F-102 Delta Dagger RTU.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In January 1975, after 14 years of service, the unit's F-102s were retired, but the unit maintained a full fleet of F-101s.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] The 111th also operated Detachment 1, 147th Fighter Group at New Orleans.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] The detachment was apart from the squadron in that it maintained constant alert status whilst facing towards Cuba.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In October 1979, in as part of the inactivation of Aerospace Defense Command, the USAF gained command responsibilities which shifted to Tactical Air Command (TAC) and a sub-organization equivalent to a numbered air force designated as Air Defense, Tactical Air Command (ADTAC).
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In 1982, the F-101s were retired and ADTAC re-equipped the 111th with the McDonnell F-4C Phantom II and continued its air defense mission.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Most of the F-4Cs the squadron received were Vietnam War veteran aircraft.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In November 1986, the F-4Cs were replaced by later-model F-4Ds.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In December 1989 the 111th FIS started receiving block 15 F-16A/B Fighting Falcon aircraft to replace their F-4Ds.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In 1992, only a few years following the acceptance of their block 15s, they converted to the Air Defense Fighter (ADF) variant of the block 15.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] On 15 March 1992 the 111th FIS was redesignated the 111th Fighter Squadron when its parent **147th Fighter Group** converted to the USAF Objective Organization plan.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Also in 1992 the 111th FS celebrated their 75th anniversary.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] To commemorate this F-16A ADF #82-1001 was painted in special markings including a big Texas flag painted on the fuselage underside.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] During September 1995, the 111th FS ended its alert detachment in New Orleans with the F-101 Voodoo, also the 147th was upgraded to a Wing, with the 111th Fighter Squadron being assigned to the new 147th Operations Group.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In late 1996 the 111th started to retire their ADF F-16s to Aerospace Maintenance and Regeneration Center (AMARC).
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] To replace these aircraft the squadron received the block 25 F-16C/D Fighting Falcon.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Transition started in September 1996 and was completed by February 1997.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] This brought a change in role which officially happened in October 1998.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] The role went from air-to-air to an air-to-ground mission.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] After returning from an Operation Southern Watch mission at Prince Sultan Air Base, Saudi Arabia in October 2000, the squadron added Precision Guided Munitions to its arsenal.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Following the 11 September 2001 terrorist attacks, four 111th Fighter Squadron aircraft were launched to escort President George W.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Bush, onboard Air Force One from Florida to Louisiana, Nebraska and back to Washington DC that same day.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] December 2001 saw the 111th deploy to Atlantic City, New Jersey, to fly Air Defense Combat Air Patrol missions over New York, Philadelphia and Washington DC in support of Operation Noble Eagle.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In August 2005 components of the 111th Fighter Squadron and 147th Fighter Wing deployed to Balad Airbase, Iraq to conduct combat operations in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom and the Global War on Terrorism.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] The 111th FS/147th FW flew 462 sorties and almost 1,900 hours in a two-month span; with a perfect record of 100% maintenance delivery (zero missed sorties), 100% mission effectiveness, and 100% weapons employment/hits under challenging combat conditions.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] In April 2007, components of the 111th Fighter Squadron and 147th Fighter Wing again deployed to Balad Airbase, Iraq for the Iraq War.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] On this deployment, the 111th Fighter Squadron flew 348 tasked sorties, plus six no-notice Close Air Support (CAS) alert scrambles and four short-notice (less than 30 minutes & not on the Air Tasking Order). pre-planned alert launches.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] With an average combat sortie lasting almost 4.42 hours, the unit accumulated a total of 1537.1 combat hours.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Maintenance delivery effectiveness for this deployment was 102% due to the inclusion of the unscheduled CAS scrambles.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Mission effectiveness and weapons employment were both once again a perfect 100%.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] During the 2005 Base Realignment and Closure Commission, it was recommended that the F-16 Block 25s be retired.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] Texas Governor, Rick Perry, reacted quickly and ensured that the unit could remain alive by securing MQ-1 Predator operations.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] The MQ-1, an unmanned aircraft, although not exactly what the 111th had hoped for, would keep the unit going well into the future.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] This view that Remotely Piloted Aircraft and those who operate them are inferior is one held by most Air National Guard units who have accepted MQ-9 assignments in lieu of being completely shut down.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] As was earlier planned in 2005, the 111th gave up its last two F-16s on 7 June 2008 and F-16 operations drew to a close.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] The MQ-1 replaced the F-16 and the parent wing was renamed the **147th Reconnaissance Wing** that same month.
[src:george-w-bush/147th-reconnaissance-wing] The 111th RS received its first MQ-9 Reaper on 28 July 2017, and the parent wing was renamed **147th Attack Wing** shortly thereafter.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] The company has been criticized over conflicts of interest related to Donald Trump Jr.'s association with the Donald Trump administration.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Within one year after Trump assumed office, companies backed by 1789 Capital received contracts valued at $735 million from the Trump administration.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Other companies invested in by 1789 Capital have received regulatory relief from the Trump administration.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] 1789 Capital was founded on October 3, 2022.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] The founders were members of the Rockbridge Network, including investment banker Omeed Malik, heiress Rebekah Mercer, and entrepreneur Chris Buskirk.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] They created the firm as a result of the 2022 Rockbridge Summit.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Blake Masters was also involved in the initial conversation, according to *Bloomberg*.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] The group chose the number 1789 to reflect the year the U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Alexandra Ulmer and Joseph Tanfani from *Reuters* remark that Peter Thiel was an instrumental force behind the creation of 1789 Capital.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Buskirk was a confidant of Thiel's, while Blake Masters, who formerly worked for Thiel Capital, was also a board member.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] The fund is intended to create a "parallel economy", a network that combines "businesses, media outlets and political organizations" associated with the America First movement.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] The firm has invested in Anduril Industries, the defense manufacturing company Hadrian, and other Thiel-backed companies.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] The firm was originally registered in Delaware.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] As of September 2025, it is still registered there, but has its main office in Palm Beach, Florida, and conducts business in the state, with the Tallahassee branch of the Corporation Service Company as their registered agent.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] They also have an office in Scottsdale, Arizona.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] The firm made its first investment into Tucker Carlson and Neil Patel's new media company in 2023.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Shortly after Donald Trump won the 2024 United States presidential election, Trump's son Donald Trump Jr. announced that he would be joining as a partner at 1789 Capital instead of joining his father in a government position.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] 1789 Capital and Type One Ventures co-hosted a fundraising event at Mar-a-Lago, which is owned by Donald Trump, on January 15, 2025, 5 days before Trump's inauguration.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] As of October 2025, the main page for the 1789 Capital website says "Funding the Next Chapter of American Exceptionalism".
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] In September 2025, the company reported its assets amounted to US$861,247,283.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] According to a May 2026 report by the Financial Times, 1789 Capital's assets under management grew from 200 million to 3.5 billion over the course of about a year — a 17‑fold increase.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] The firm, which operates under an "America First" brand, invests in artificial intelligence, defense technology, and real estate.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Since the start of the second Trump administration, companies backed by the firm have received more than 735 million in federal contracts, including a 620 million loan from the Pentagon.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] 1789 Capital describes itself as promoting "patriotic capitalism", investing in companies that are "anti-woke" and "America First".
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] The firm also invests in "almost all of Elon Musk's companies", including Neuralink, X (formerly Twitter), xAI, and SpaceX.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] 1789 Capital invested in GrabAGun, an online firearms retailer which Malik has called "the Amazon of guns", partly because the company aligns with 1789 Capital's values.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] The firm does not invest in companies such as OpenAI that they deem not supportive enough of the Trump administration.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] In August 2025, 1789 Capital invested in Vulcan Elements, a rare earth magnet company with 30 employees.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Three months later, Vulcan Elements received a $620 million loan from the U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Department of Defense to increase the supply of magnets for industries.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] This was the largest loan given by the Pentagon’s Office of Strategic Capital.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] In October 2025, Colombier Acquisition Corp.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] III, Malik's special purpose acquisition company (SPAC) that has been involved in 1789 Capital's previous investments, filed for an initial public offering (IPO) for the New York Stock Exchange, with an initial share price of $10 and 26,000 units intended to raise US$260 million.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Roth Capital Partners was the underwriter for the move, and Chamath Palihapitiya was reportedly planned to be a director for the company.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] The firm was founded by Chris Buskirk, Omeed Malik, and Rebekah Mercer.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Jordan Cohen is listed as partner and COO.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Other partners include Paul Abrahimzadeh, Andy Nasser, Donald Trump Jr., Joe Voboril, and Emanuel Zareh.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Venture capitalist Blake Masters was previously listed as a member of the Board of Advisors, but has since been removed from the website.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Early backers included Marc Andreessen, Charlie Kirk, and Clay Travis.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] 1789 Capital has a South Korea-based think tank called 1789 Partners.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] CEO of the group is Park Byung-eun, who is also involved with Rockbridge Korea, the Seoul-based branch of the Rockbridge Network.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Chung Yong-jin of Shinsegae and Rockbridge Korea is also leading the project.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Multiple media outlets, financial figures, government watchdogs, ethics experts, and various Democrats have criticized 1789 Capital for its ties to the Trump administration.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] The Revolving Door Project (RDP) has also raised concerns about 1789 Capital.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Around August or September 2025, Rebecca Ballhaus of *The Wall Street Journal* (WSJ) filed a broad FOIA request to the SEC, asking for "any records involving 1789 Capital, including any emails and text messages to or from 1789 Capital domains and any records that mention 1789 Capital." John A.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] In October 2025, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that 1789 Capital had "tried to sell sponsorships for a conference pitched to companies as the 'Inaugural U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Summit,' during which it said Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent would unveil the Treasury Department’s artificial-intelligence strategy." The U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Treasury [was] being used for an event that appear[ed] to result in the personal gain of outside actors”.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Some have criticized 1789 Capital's investment into BlinkRX, since the firm–and Trump Jr.–are likely to benefit from Donald Trump's May 2025 executive order directing pharmaceutical manufacturers to offer an online option for people to purchase prescription drugs without using insurance.
[src:george-w-bush/1789-capital] Other critics include Richard Painter and Ann Skeet.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] The **1856 Republican National Convention** was a presidential nominating convention that met from June 17 to June 19, 1856, at Musical Fund Hall at 808 Locust Street in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] It was the first national nominating convention of the Republican Party, founded two years earlier in 1854.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] It was held to nominate the party's candidates for president and vice president in the 1856 election.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont, a former United States Senator from California, for president, and former Senator William L.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Dayton of New Jersey for vice president.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] The convention also appointed members of the newly established Republican National Committee.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] The Republican Party had been organized by opponents of the expansion of slavery in the territories following the passage of the 1854 Kansas–Nebraska Act.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Chase, and Charles Sumner all taking their names out of consideration, Frémont entered the Republican convention as the front-runner for the presidential nomination.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont had previously been nominated by the North American Party, which consisted of anti-slavery members of the American Party who were unwilling to support the American Party candidate, Millard Fillmore.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Though Associate Justice John McLean of Ohio had the backing of some delegates, Frémont clinched the presidential nomination on the first formal ballot of the Republican convention.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Dayton was nominated on the first formal vice-presidential ballot, defeating former Congressman Abraham Lincoln of Illinois and several other candidates.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] The Republican ticket carried several Northern states in the general election, but the Democratic ticket of James Buchanan and John C.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] On June 19, 1855, a small gathering of like-minded individuals met in Washington, D.C. where they passed a resolution noting the recent abrogation of "all compromises, real or imaginary" by the opening of Kansas Territory and Nebraska Territory to the possible institution of slavery.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] The 22-member Republican National Committee, which included one representative from each state attending the Pittsburgh Convention, met in plenary session on March 27, 1856, at the Willard Hotel in Washington, D.C., and issued a call for a formal presidential nominating convention.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] This was slated to begin on June 17, 1856, in Philadelphia.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Each state organization was to be allocated six at-large delegates, plus three delegates for each congressional district.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] The candidates to be nominated by the new Republican party were first nominated by the anti-slavery rump of the American Party.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] American party members from the North who were opposed to slavery formed their own party after the nomination of former President Millard Fillmore in Philadelphia.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] This party called for its national convention to be held in New York, New York, just before the Republican National Convention.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Party leaders hoped to nominate a joint ticket with the Republicans to defeat Buchanan.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] The national convention was held on June 12 to 20, 1856 in New York.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont was the favorite to attain the Republican nomination there was a considerable desire for the North American party to nominate him, but it was feared that in doing so they may possibly injure his chances to actually become the Republican nominee.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] The delegates voted repeatedly on a nominee for president without a result.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Banks was nominated for president on the 10th ballot over John C.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont and John McLean, with the understanding that he would withdraw from the race and endorse John C.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont once he had won the Republican nomination.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] The delegates, preparing to return home, unanimously nominated Frémont on the 11th ballot shortly after his nomination by the Republican Party in Philadelphia.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] The chairman of the convention, William F.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Johnston, had been nominated to run for vice-president, but later withdrew when the North Americans and the Republicans failed to find an acceptable accommodation between him and the Republican nominee, William Dayton.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] The first Republican National Convention was held in the Musical Fund Hall in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, on June 17–19, 1856.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] It was led by Robert Emmet as temporary chairman and Henry S.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] The convention approved an anti-slavery platform that called for congressional sovereignty in the territories, an end to polygamy in Mormon settlements, and federal assistance for a transcontinental railroad.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Kentucky was the only southern state to have a delegation at the convention.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont, John McLean, Nathaniel Banks, William Seward, Salmon Chase, and Charles Sumner all were considered by those at the convention, but the latter three requested that their names be withdrawn.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] The Massachusetts delegation resolved in a morning meeting to vote unanimously for Banks.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] However, the name of Banks was then authoritatively and peremptorily withdrawn and the delegation resolved as a unit to support Frémont.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] McLean's name was initially withdrawn by his manager Rufus Spalding, but the withdrawal was rescinded at the strong behest of the Pennsylvania delegation led by Thaddeus Stevens.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont was nominated for president overwhelmingly on the formal ballot.
[src:george-w-bush/1856-republican-national-convention] Dayton was nominated for vice president over Abraham Lincoln.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The **1860 Republican National Convention** was a presidential nominating convention that met May 16–18 in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] It was held to nominate the Republican Party's candidates for president and vice president in the 1860 election.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The convention selected former representative Abraham Lincoln of Illinois for president and Senator Hannibal Hamlin of Maine for vice president.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Entering the 1860 convention, Senator William H.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Seward of New York was generally regarded as the front-runner, but Lincoln, Governor Salmon P.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Chase of Ohio, former representative Edward Bates of Missouri, and Senator Simon Cameron of Pennsylvania all commanded support from a significant share of delegates.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Seward led on the first ballot but fell short of a majority, while Lincoln finished in a strong second place.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Cameron's delegates shifted to Lincoln on the second ballot, leaving Lincoln essentially tied with Seward.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln clinched the nomination on the third ballot after consolidating support from more delegates who had backed candidates other than Seward.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Hamlin was nominated on the second vice presidential ballot, defeating Cassius Clay of Kentucky and several other candidates.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The ticket of Lincoln and Hamlin went on to win the 1860 general election.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] After taking office in 1861, Lincoln appointed all four of his major opponents to his cabinet: Seward for secretary of state, Chase for secretary of the treasury (and later for chief justice), Bates for attorney general, and Cameron for secretary of war.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] By 1860 the dissolution of the Whig Party in America had become an accomplished fact, with establishment Whig politicians, former Free Soilers, and a certain number of anti-Catholic populists from the Know Nothing movement flocking to the banner of the fledgling anti-slavery Republican Party.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] While 1856 Republican presidential nominee John C.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Frémont had met with failure, party gains were made throughout the Northern United States as the sectional crisis over slavery intensified.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Morgan were interested in holding the 1860 convention in a border state.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Party leaders sought to hold their 1860 nominating convention in the burgeoning Middle Western trade center of Chicago, then a city of some 110,000 people.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The city had no sufficiently large meeting hall, so an appropriation was made for a temporary wood-frame assembly hall – known as the "Wigwam" – to seat ten thousand delegates, guests, and observers.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The rapidly designed and constructed building proved well fit for the purpose, featuring excellent lines of sight and stellar acoustics, allowing even an ordinary speaker to be heard throughout the room.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The Convention commanded the interest and attention of a multitude of curious citizens who crowded the "Wigwam" to the rafters.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Delegations were seated by state and the gathering was virtually devoid of Southern participation, with no delegations attending from the slave states of North Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee, Arkansas, Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi, Louisiana, and Florida.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Some 86 votes were apportioned to the six states of New England.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Slave and border states with substantial delegations under the rules (but with small actual party organizations) included Kentucky (23), Virginia (23), and Missouri (18).
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The total of all credentialed delegate votes was 466.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] With the convention called to order on May 16, former U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Representative David Wilmot of Pennsylvania was elected temporary chairman of the gathering.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] He had been the author in 1848 of the Wilmot Proviso which would have banned slavery from new states incorporated into the Union.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Organizational tasks filled the rest of the first day's activities, including the appointment of a Credentials Committee and a Resolutions Committee.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] There were no contested seats although a delegation purporting to represent the state of Texas was ruled ineligible by the Credentials Committee.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] A Platform Committee was also named, including one delegate from every state and territory in attendance.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] This committee began its work at once and completed its task with a report on the evening of the second day, May 17.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The platform was drawn up by the Platform Committee chaired by Judge William Jessup of Pennsylvania.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The reading of the platform was received with stormy applause and an immediate move followed to adopt the document unanimously and without amendments.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The matter was hastily reconsidered by the convention, and with the addition of the amendment the disgruntled Mr.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Giddings returned to his seat, crisis resolved.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The 1860 Republican platform consisted of 17 declarations of principle, of which 10 dealt directly with the issues of "free soil", slavery, the Fugitive Slave Act, and the preservation of the Union, while the remaining 7 dealt with other issues.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Clauses 12 through 16 of the platform called for a protective tariff, enactment of the Homestead Act, maintaining the current naturalization laws and full rights to all "native or naturalized" citizens, internal improvements, and the construction of a Pacific railroad.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] In addition to the preservation of the Union, all five of these additional promises were enacted by the Thirty-seventh Congress and implemented by Abraham Lincoln or the presidents who immediately succeeded him.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The Republican National Convention met in mid-May 1860, after the Democrats had been forced to adjourn their convention in Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] With the Democrats in disarray and a sweep of the Northern states possible, the Republicans felt confident going into their convention in Chicago.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Seward from New York was considered the front-runner, followed Salmon P.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Chase from Ohio, and Missouri's Edward Bates.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Abraham Lincoln from Illinois, was lesser known, and was not considered to have a good chance against Seward.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Seward had been governor and senator of New York, was from firm Whig backgrounds, and was a very able politician.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Clay, and Benjamin Wade, who might be able to win if the convention deadlocked.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] As the convention developed, however, it was revealed that frontrunners Seward, Chase, and Bates had each alienated factions of the Republican Party.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Seward had been painted as a radical, and his speeches on slavery predicted inevitable conflict, which spooked moderate delegates.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] He also was firmly opposed to nativism, which further weakened his position.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] He had also been abandoned by his longtime friend and political ally Horace Greeley, publisher of the influential *New-York Tribune*.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Chase, a former Democrat, had alienated many of the former Whigs by his coalition with the Democrats in the late 1840s.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] He had also opposed tariffs demanded by Pennsylvania, and even had opposition from his own delegation from Ohio.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] However, Chase's firm antislavery stance made him popular with the radical Republicans.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] But what he had in policy he lacked in charisma and political acumen.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Bates' candidacy was pushed by Francis Preston Blair and Francis Preston Blair Jr. despite Bates not being a member of the party.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] They had the Republican parties of Missouri and Maryland send delegations pledged to Bates.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Greeley and Schuyler Colfax were interested in his candidacy, but he failed to receive a large amount of support from northern or border state delegates.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The conservative Bates was an unlikely candidate.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln was not unknown; he had gained prominence in the Lincoln–Douglas debates, and had served as a member of the U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] He had been quietly eyeing a run since the Lincoln–Douglas debates in 1858, ensuring that the debates were widely published, and that a biography of himself was published.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] He gained great notability with his February 1860 Cooper Union speech, which may have ensured him the nomination.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] At that time he had not yet announced his intentions to run, but it was a superb speech.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Delivered in Seward's home state, and attended by Greeley, Lincoln used the speech to show that the Republican party was a party of moderates, not crazed fanatics as the South and Democrats claimed.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Afterwards, Lincoln was in much demand for speaking engagements.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] As the convention approached, Lincoln did not campaign very actively, as the "office was expected to seek the man".
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] So it did at the Illinois state convention in downstate Decatur, a week before the national convention.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Young politician Richard Oglesby had secretly found several fence rails from the Hanks-Lincoln farm that Lincoln may have split as a youngster, and paraded them into the convention with a banner that proclaimed Lincoln to be "The Rail Candidate" for president.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln received a thunderous ovation, surpassing the expectations of him and his political allies.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Even with such support from his home state, Lincoln faced a difficult task if he was to win the nomination.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] He set about ensuring that he was the second choice of most delegates, realizing that the first round of voting at the convention was unlikely to produce a clear winner.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] He engineered that the convention would happen in Chicago, which would be inherently friendly to the Illinois-based Lincoln.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] He also made sure that the Illinois delegation would vote as a bloc for him.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln did not attend the convention in person, and left the task of delegate wrangling to his friends Leonard Swett, Ward Hill Lamon, and David Davis.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln's team even printed counterfeit convention tickets, which they handed out to his supporters.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] During the night of May 17–18, they worked frantically to win anti-Seward delegates for Lincoln.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] They showed that Lincoln already had the most support after Seward, which persuaded some.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] They also made a deal with Simon Cameron of Pennsylvania, who recognized that he had no chance of winning the nomination himself.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Cameron controlled the Pennsylvania delegation, and he offered to trade his support for the promise of a cabinet position for himself and control of Federal patronage in Pennsylvania.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln did not want to make any such deal; from Springfield, he telegraphed to Davis "I authorize no bargains and will be bound by none".
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Despite this restriction, Davis reached an understanding with Cameron, which eventually led to Cameron's appointment as Secretary of War.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] The next day (May 18), when voting for the nomination began, Seward led on the first ballot with Lincoln a distant second.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] But on the second ballot, the Pennsylvania delegation switched to Lincoln, as well as some other delegates, putting him in a near-tie with Seward.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln's combination of a moderate stance on slavery, long support for economic issues, his western origins, and strong oratory proved to be exactly what the delegates wanted in a president.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] On the third ballot on May 18, Lincoln secured the nomination overwhelmingly.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Senator Hannibal Hamlin from Maine was nominated for vice-president, defeating Cassius M.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Among other accounts, an article, entitled "The Four Votes", published in the May 19, 1860, edition of the *Chicago Press and Tribune* attests that after seeing how close Lincoln was to the 234 votes needed, Robert K.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Enos, a member of the Ohio delegation, was responsible for getting three fellow Ohio delegates to announce after the close of the third ballot that they were shifting their four votes to Lincoln, giving him sufficient votes to win the nomination.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] This triggered an avalanche towards Lincoln on the fourth ballot, with a final count of 350 votes for Lincoln out of 466 cast.
[src:george-w-bush/1860-republican-national-convention] Senator Hannibal Hamlin of Maine was nominated for vice president, defeating Cassius M.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] The **1864 National Union National Convention** was the United States presidential nominating convention of the National Union Party, which met in Baltimore, Maryland on June 7 and 8, 1864.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] National Union was the name adopted by the main faction of the Republican Party in a coalition with many, if not most, War Democrats and Unconditional Unionists after some Republicans and War Democrats nominated John C.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] Frémont over Lincoln a few weeks earlier.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] The National Union renominated Abraham Lincoln for president and Andrew Johnson was nominated for vice president.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] During the convention, the party adopted a platform calling for a victorious end in the ongoing Civil War, the eradication of slavery by constitutional amendment and the enforcement of the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] The party name was created in May 1864, during the Civil War, ahead of the 1864 presidential election, in which President Abraham Lincoln, then a Republican, was running for reelection.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] Frémont, who had been the Republicans' first presidential nominee during the 1856 election.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] It was hoped that this act would cause someone other than Lincoln to gain the Republican nomination.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] Republicans loyal to Lincoln created a new name for their party at the convention in Baltimore, Maryland, during the first week in June 1864, in order to accommodate the War Democrats who supported the war and wished to separate themselves from the Copperheads.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] The convention dropped then-Vice President Hannibal Hamlin, a Radical Republican from the ticket, and chose War Democrat Andrew Johnson as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] The National Unionists hoped that the new party and the Lincoln–Johnson ticket would stress the national character of the war.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] The party supported a Platform of 11 resolutions.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] Dennis Francis Murphy, member of the Official Corps of Reporters for the U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] On the first ballot, Missouri delegates cast their 22 votes for General Ulysses S.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] The Missourians quickly changed their votes to make Lincoln's renomination unanimous.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] Though Hamlin was willing to serve another term as vice president, he privately made it known that he was willing to step aside if a candidate who would be a greater electoral asset to Lincoln could be found.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] The convention therefore nominated Andrew Johnson, the military governor of Tennessee.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] Lincoln had refused to weigh in on his preferred running mate, and the convention chose to nominate Johnson, a Southern War Democrat, in order to boost the party's appeal to Unionists of both parties.
[src:george-w-bush/1864-national-union-national-convention] In keeping with the tradition of the time, Lincoln did not attend the convention.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] The **1868 Republican National Convention** of the Republican Party of the United States was held in Crosby's Opera House, Chicago, Cook County, Illinois, on May 20 to May 21, 1868.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] Grant was the unanimous choice of the Republican convention delegates for president.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] For vice president the delegates chose Speaker Schuyler Colfax, who was Grant's choice.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] In Grant's acceptance telegram, a letter to then President of the Republican National Convention Joseph R.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] Republicans, led by their Radical faction, had scored decisive victories in the 1866 elections.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] If that trend continued in the 1867 elections, then the party's presidential nomination would likely go to a Radical like Chief Justice Salmon P.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] Chase had the support of important figures like Senator Charles Sumner and financier Jay Cooke.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] More moderate Republicans, such as Senator William P.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] Fessenden, Charles Francis Adams Jr., and *The New York Times*, had interpreted the 1866 elections not as a mandate for radicalism, but as a rejection of President Andrew Johnson's programs and personality; therefore, they were wary of a Radical nominee.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] The Grant candidacy, though, took on momentum in the wake of the state elections in 1867.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] The electorate rejected the Radical Republican agenda by voting for Democratic control in the key Northern states of New York, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, and by rejecting black manhood suffrage amendments in Kansas and Ohio.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] The election results bolstered the case of the moderate Republicans and seemed to close the door to a Radical nominee.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] Georges Clemenceau, a Paris Temps journalist who would later be the French premier, reported accurately that "The real victims of the victory of the Democrats are Mr.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] As Republicans convened in Chicago in May 1868, Grant had no serious opposition for the nomination; he was nominated unanimously on the first ballot.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] Colfax was selected for vice president on the fifth ballot.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] Colfax was popular among Republicans for his friendly character, party loyalty, and Radical views on Reconstruction.
[src:george-w-bush/1868-republican-national-convention] Wilson received a large amount of support from the southern delegations.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] The **1872 Republican National Convention** was held in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, June 5–6, 1872.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] Grant was unanimously nominated for reelection by the convention's 752 delegates.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] Massachusetts Senator Henry Wilson from Massachusetts replaced Vice President Schuyler Colfax as the Republican vice presidential nominee.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] Vice President Colfax was considered a potential rival to Grant for the presidential nomination.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] Although Colfax declared himself open to the prospect should Grant decide not to run for a second term, his stance alienated him from both the President and his many supporters.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] Grant's nomination was co-seconded by William Henry Grey of Arkansas, the first African-American to address a major U.S. political party national convention.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] Grant received the nomination unanimously on the first ballot.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] Grant's re-nomination would be the last time the Republican party nominated a candidate unanimously until McKinley's re-nomination in 1900.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] The late 19th century saw a massive and nationwide growth of the temperance movement, and until 1872 the Republican Party had not formally adopted a stance on the prohibition of alcohol.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] Famous German American editor and political figure Hermann Raster of Chicago wrote a passionate and carefully worded resolution, dubbed the *Raster Resolution*, for the 1872 convention.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] The resolution attacked the temperance movement and solidified the Republican Party's opposition to prohibition, and it was inserted in condensed form as the sixteenth section of the official platform.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] Colfax's chances for re-nomination were further damaged when a small movement within the Liberal Republican Party sought to enter his name for their presidential nomination.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] While the rumors of Colfax's nomination for either party's nomination amounted to little more than speculation, it likely cost him his bid for re-nomination.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] Colfax narrowly missed the mark by garnering 308.5 delegates compared to Massachusetts Senator Henry Wilson's 399.5 on a revised first ballot.
[src:george-w-bush/1872-republican-national-convention] President Grant was among many notables who remained on the sideline during the vice presidential balloting.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Born into the prominent Bush family in New Haven, Connecticut, Bush flew warplanes in the Texas Air National Guard in his twenties.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] After graduating from Harvard Business School in 1975, he worked in the oil industry.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He later co-owned the Major League Baseball team Texas Rangers before being elected governor of Texas in 1994.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] As governor, Bush successfully sponsored legislation for tort reform, increased education funding, set higher standards for schools, and reformed the criminal justice system.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He also helped make Texas the leading producer of wind-generated electricity in the United States.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In the 2000 presidential election, he defeated Democratic incumbent vice president Al Gore while losing the popular vote after a narrow and contested United States Electoral College win, which involved the Supreme Court decision *Bush v.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In his first term, Bush signed a major tax-cut program and an education-reform bill, the No Child Left Behind Act.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He pushed for socially conservative efforts such as the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act, restrictions on same-sex marriage, and faith-based initiatives.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He also initiated the President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief, in 2003, to address the global AIDS epidemic.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] The September 11 attacks during 2001 decisively reshaped his administration, resulting in the start of the war on terror and the creation of the Department of Homeland Security.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush ordered the invasion of Afghanistan in an effort to overthrow the Taliban, destroy al-Qaeda, and capture Osama bin Laden.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He signed the Patriot Act, expanding surveillance powers for suspected terrorists.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He also ordered the 2003 invasion of Iraq to overthrow Saddam Hussein's regime, citing claims that it possessed weapons of mass destruction and had ties with al-Qaeda.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush later signed the Medicare Modernization Act, which created Medicare Part D.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In 2004, Bush was re-elected president in a close race, beating Democratic opponent John Kerry and winning the popular vote.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] During his second term, Bush negotiated various free trade agreements, appointed John Roberts and Samuel Alito to the Supreme Court, and sought major changes to Social Security and immigration laws, both of which ultimately failed in Congress.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He was widely criticized for his administration's handling of Hurricane Katrina and revelations of torture against detainees at Abu Ghraib prison in Iraq.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Amid his unpopularity, the Democrats regained control of Congress in the 2006 elections.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Meanwhile, the wars in Afghanistan and Iraq continued.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In January 2007, Bush launched a surge of troops in Iraq.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] As his presidency came to a close, the country experienced a financial crisis, resulting in the Great Recession, prompting his administration and Congress to push through emergency economic measures aimed at stabilizing the financial system, including the Troubled Asset Relief Program.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] After his second term, Bush returned to Texas, where he has maintained a low public profile.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] At various points in his presidency, he was both among the most popular and among the least popular presidents in U.S. history.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He received the highest recorded approval ratings in the wake of the September 11 attacks, and one of the lowest ratings during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush left office as one of the most unpopular U.S. presidents; however, public opinion of him has improved in his post-presidency.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Scholars and historians generally rank Bush as a below-average president.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] George Walker Bush was born on July 6, 1946, at Grace-New Haven Hospital in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He is the first child of George Herbert Walker Bush and Barbara Pierce, and was raised in Midland and Houston, Texas.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] His five siblings are Robin, Jeb, Neil, Marvin and Dorothy.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Robin died from leukemia at the age of three in 1953.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] His paternal grandfather, Prescott Bush, was a U.S. senator from Connecticut.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] His father was Ronald Reagan's vice president from 1981 to 1989 and the 41st president of the United States from 1989 to 1993.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush has English and German ancestry, along with more distant Dutch, Welsh, Irish, French, and Scottish roots.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush attended public schools in Midland, Texas, until the family moved to Houston after he had completed seventh grade.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He then spent two years at The Kinkaid School, a college-preparatory school in Piney Point Village, Texas.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush later attended Phillips Academy, a boarding school in Andover, Massachusetts, where he played baseball and was the head cheerleader during his senior year.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He attended Yale University from 1964 to 1968, graduating with a Bachelor of Arts degree in history.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] During this time, he was a cheerleader and a member of the Delta Kappa Epsilon, serving as the president of the fraternity during his senior year.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush became a member of the Skull and Bones society as a senior.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush was a rugby union player and was on Yale's 1st XV.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He characterized himself as an average student.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] His grade point average during his first three years at Yale was 77, and he had a similar average under a nonnumerical rating system in his final year.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In the fall of 1973, Bush entered Harvard Business School.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He graduated in 1975 with a Master of Business Administration.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He is the only U.S. president to have earned that degree.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush was engaged to Cathryn Lee Wolfman in 1967, but the engagement did not last.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush and Wolfman remained on good terms after the end of the relationship.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] While Bush was at a backyard barbecue in 1977, friends introduced him to Laura Welch, a schoolteacher and librarian.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] After a three-month courtship, she accepted his marriage proposal and they wed on November 5 of that year.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush left his family's Episcopal Church to join his wife's United Methodist Church.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] On November 25, 1981, Laura Bush gave birth to fraternal twin daughters, Barbara and Jenna.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush describes being challenged by Billy Graham to consider faith in Jesus "Christ as the risen Lord", how he began reading the Bible daily, "surrendering" to "the Almighty", that "faith is a walk" and that he was "moved by God's love".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Before his marriage, Bush repeatedly abused alcohol.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] On September 4, 1976, he was pulled over near his family's summer home in Kennebunkport, Maine, for driving under the influence of alcohol.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He was arrested for DUI, was fined $150, and received a brief suspension of his Maine driver's license.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush said that his wife has had a stabilizing effect on his life, and he attributes his decision to give up alcohol in 1986 to her influence.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush has been an avid reader throughout his adult life, preferring biographies and histories.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] During his presidency, Bush read the Bible daily, though at the end of his second term he said on television that he is "not a literalist" about Bible interpretation.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Walt Harrington, a journalist, recalled seeing "books by John Fowles, F.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Scott Fitzgerald, James Joyce, and Gore Vidal lying about, as well as biographies of Willa Cather and Queen Victoria" in his home when Bush was a Texas oilman.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Other activities include cigar smoking and golf.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] One of his best-known projects is a collection of 43 paintings of immigrants, titled *Out of Many, One*.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Another painting project was *Portraits of Courage: A Commander in Chief's Tribute to America's Warrior*.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In May 1968, Bush joined the United States Air Force and was commissioned into the Texas Air National Guard.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] After two years of training in active-duty service, he was assigned to Houston, flying Convair F-102s with the 147th Reconnaissance Wing out of Ellington Field Joint Reserve Base.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In June 2005, the Department of Defense released all the records of Bush's Texas Air National Guard service, which remain in its official archives.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In late 1972 and early 1973, he drilled with the 187th Fighter Wing of the Alabama Air National Guard.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He had moved to Montgomery, Alabama, to work on the unsuccessful U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In 1972, Bush was suspended from flying for failure to take a scheduled physical exam.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He was honorably discharged from the Air Force Reserve on November 21, 1974.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush remains the most recent president to have served in the military.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In 1977, Bush established Arbusto Energy, a small oil exploration company, which began operations in 1978.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He later changed the name to Bush Exploration.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In 1984, his company merged with the larger Spectrum 7, and Bush became chairman.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] The company was hurt by decreased oil prices, and it folded into Harken Energy Corporation, with Bush becoming a member of Harken's board of directors.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Questions of possible insider trading involving Harken arose, but a Securities and Exchange Commission investigation concluded that the information Bush had at the time of his stock sale was not sufficient to constitute insider trading.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In April 1989, Bush arranged for a group of investors to purchase a controlling interest of Major League Baseball's Texas Rangers for $89 million and invested $500,000 himself to start.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He then was managing general partner for five years.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He actively led the team's projects and regularly attended its games, often choosing to sit in the open stands with fans.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush's sale of his shares in the Rangers in 1998 brought him over $15 million from his initial $800,000 investment.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In the early or mid 1990s, before his gubernatorial campaign, Bush briefly considered a candidacy to become the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] House of Representatives from Texas's 19th congressional district.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Mahon, had held the district for the Democratic Party since 1935.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush's opponent, Kent Hance, portrayed him as out of touch with rural Texans, and Bush lost the election, receiving 46.8 percent of the vote to Hance's 53.2 percent.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush and his family moved to Washington, D.C., in 1988 to work on his father's campaign for the U.S. presidency.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He was a campaign advisor and liaison to the media, and assisted his father by campaigning across the country.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In December 1991, Bush was one of seven people named by his father to run his father's 1992 presidential re-election campaign as a campaign advisor.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] The previous month, his father had asked him to tell White House chief of staff John H.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush declared his candidacy for the 1994 Texas gubernatorial election at the same time his brother Jeb sought the governorship in Florida.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] His campaign focused on four themes: welfare reform, tort reform, crime reduction, and education improvement.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush's campaign advisers were Karen Hughes, Joe Allbaugh, and Karl Rove.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] After easily winning the Republican primary, Bush faced popular Democratic incumbent governor Ann Richards.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In the course of the campaign, Bush pledged to sign a bill allowing Texans to obtain permits to carry concealed weapons.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Richards had vetoed the bill, but Bush signed it into law after he became governor.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] *The Atlantic*, and others, connected the lesbian rumor to Karl Rove, but Rove denied being involved.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush won the general election with 53.5 percent of the vote against Richards' 45.9 percent.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush used a budget surplus to push through Texas's largest tax cut, $2 billion.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He extended government funding for organizations providing education on the dangers of alcohol and drug use and abuse, and helping to reduce domestic violence.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] His administration lowered the age at which juveniles can be sent to adult court for serious crimes to 14.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush presided over 152 executions, more than any previous governor in modern American history; critics such as Helen Prejean argue that he failed to give serious consideration to clemency requests.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Critics also contended that during his tenure, Texas ranked near the bottom in environmental evaluations.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Supporters pointed to his efforts to raise the salaries of teachers and improve educational test scores.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In 1999, Bush signed a law that required electric retailers to buy a certain amount of energy from renewable sources (RPS), which helped Texas eventually become the leading producer of wind-powered electricity in the U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In 1998, Bush won re-election with a record 68 percent of the vote.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He became the first governor in Texas history to be elected to two consecutive four-year terms.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] During his second term, Bush promoted faith-based organizations and enjoyed high approval ratings, which ranged between 62 and 81 percent.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He proclaimed June 10, 2000, to be Jesus Day in Texas, a day on which he urged all Texans to "answer the call to serve those in need".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Throughout Bush's first term, he was the focus of national attention as a potential future presidential candidate.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Following his re-election, speculation soared, and within a year he decided to seek the 2000 Republican presidential nomination.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush portrayed himself as a compassionate conservative, implying he was more centrist than other Republicans.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He campaigned on a platform which included bringing integrity and honor back to the White House, increasing the size of the military, cutting taxes, improving education, and aiding minorities.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] By early 2000, the race had centered on Bush and Arizona senator John McCain.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush won the Iowa caucuses and, although heavily favored to win the New Hampshire primary, trailed McCain by 19% and lost.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Despite this, he regained momentum and effectively became the front runner after the South Carolina primary, which according to *The Boston Globe* made history for his campaign's negativity.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] *The New York Times* described it as a smear campaign.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] On July 25, 2000, Bush surprised some observers when he selected Dick Cheney – a former White House chief of staff, U.S. representative, and secretary of defense – to be his running mate.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] At the time, Cheney was serving as head of Bush's vice presidential search committee.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Soon after at the 2000 Republican National Convention, Bush and Cheney were officially nominated by the Republican Party.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush continued to campaign across the country and touted his record as Governor of Texas.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] During his campaign, Bush criticized his Democratic opponent, incumbent vice president Al Gore, over gun control and taxation.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] When the election returns were tallied on November 7, Bush had won 29 states, including Florida.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] The closeness of the Florida outcome led to a recount.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] The initial recount also went to Bush, but the outcome was tied up in lower courts for a month until eventually reaching the U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] On December 9, in the controversial *Bush v.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Gore* ruling, the Court reversed a Florida Supreme Court decision that had ordered a third count, and stopped an ordered statewide hand recount based on the argument that the use of different standards among Florida's counties violated the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] The machine recount showed that Bush had won the Florida vote by a margin of 537 votes out of six million casts.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Although he had received 543,895 fewer individual nationwide votes than Gore, Bush won the election, receiving 271 electoral votes to Gore's 266 (Gore had actually been awarded 267 votes by the states pledged to him plus the District of Columbia, but one D.C. elector abstained).
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush was the first person to win a U.S. presidential election with fewer popular votes than another candidate since Benjamin Harrison in 1888.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In his 2004 bid for re-election, Bush commanded broad support in the Republican Party and did not encounter a primary challenge.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He appointed Ken Mehlman as campaign manager, and Karl Rove devised a political strategy.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Bush also called for the implementation of a guest worker program for immigrants, which was criticized by conservatives.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] The Bush campaign advertised across the U.S. against Democratic candidates, including Bush's emerging opponent, Massachusetts senator John Kerry.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Kerry and other Democrats attacked Bush on the Iraq War, and accused him of failing to stimulate the economy and job growth.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] The Bush campaign portrayed Kerry as a staunch liberal who would raise taxes and increase the size of government.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] The Bush campaign continuously criticized Kerry's seemingly contradictory statements on the war in Iraq, and argued that Kerry lacked the decisiveness and vision necessary for success in the war on terror.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] Following the resignation of CIA director George Tenet in 2004, Bush nominated Porter Goss to head the agency.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] The White House ordered Goss to purge agency officers who were disloyal to the administration.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] After Goss' appointment, many of the CIA's senior agents were fired or quit.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] The CIA has been accused of deliberately leaking classified information to undermine the 2004 election.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] In the election, Bush carried 31 of 50 states, receiving 286 electoral votes.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p01] He won an absolute majority of the popular vote (50.7% to Kerry's 48.3%).
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush had originally outlined an ambitious domestic agenda, but his priorities were significantly altered following the September 11 attacks.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Wars were begun in Afghanistan and Iraq, and there were significant domestic debates regarding immigration, healthcare, Social Security, economic policy, and treatment of terrorist detainees.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Over an eight-year period, Bush's once-high approval ratings steadily declined, while his disapproval numbers increased significantly.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In 2007, the United States entered the longest post-World War II recession.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush took office during a period of economic recession in the wake of the bursting of the dot-com bubble.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The September 11 terrorist attacks also impacted the economy.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] His administration increased federal government spending from $1.789 trillion to $2.983 trillion (66%), while revenues increased from $2.025 trillion to $2.524 trillion (from 2000 to 2008).
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Individual income tax revenues increased by 14%, corporate tax revenues by 50%, and customs and duties by 40%.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Discretionary defense spending was increased by 107%, discretionary domestic spending by 62%, Medicare spending by 131%, social security by 51%, and income security spending by 130%.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Cyclically adjusted, revenues rose by 35% and spending by 65%.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The increase in spending was more than under any predecessor since Lyndon B.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The number of economic regulation governmental workers increased by 91,196.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The surplus in fiscal year 2000 was $237 billion – the third consecutive surplus and the largest surplus ever.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In 2001, Bush's budget estimated that there would be a $5.6 trillion surplus over the next ten years.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Facing congressional opposition, Bush held town hall-style meetings across the U.S. to increase public support for his plan for a $1.35 trillion tax cut program, one of the largest tax cuts in U.S. history.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush argued that unspent government funds should be returned to taxpayers, saying "the surplus is not the government's money.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The surplus is the people's money." Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan warned of a recession and Bush stated that a tax cut would stimulate the economy and create jobs.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] O'Neill opposed some of the tax cuts on the basis they would contribute to budget deficits and undermine Social Security.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] O'Neill disputes the claim, made in Bush's book *Decision Points*, that he never openly disagreed with him on planned tax cuts.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] By 2003, the economy showed signs of improvement, though job growth remained stagnant.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Between 2001 and 2008, GDP grew at an average annual rate of 2.125%, less than for past business cycles.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush entered office with the Dow Jones Industrial Average at 10,587, and the average peaked in October 2007 at over 14,000.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] When Bush left office, the average was at 7,949, one of the lowest levels of his presidency.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Only four other U.S. presidents have left office with the stock market lower than when they began.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Unemployment originally rose from 4.2% in January 2001 to 6.3% in June 2003, but subsequently dropped to 4.5% in July 2007.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Adjusted for inflation, median household income dropped by $1,175 between 2000 and 2007, while Professor Ken Homa of Georgetown University noted that "Median real after-tax household income went up two percent".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] By October 2008, due to increases in spending, the U.S. national debt had risen to $11.3 trillion, more than doubling it since 2000.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Most debt was accumulated as a result of what became known as the "Bush tax cuts" and increased national security spending.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In March 2006, then-senator Barack Obama said when he voted against raising the debt ceiling: "The fact that we are here today to debate raising America's debt limit is a sign of leadership failure." By the end of Bush's presidency, unemployment climbed to 7.2%.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In December 2007, the United States entered the longest post–World War II recession, caused by a housing market correction, a subprime mortgage crisis, soaring oil prices, and other factors.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In February 2008, 63,000 jobs were lost, a five-year record, and in November, over 500,000 jobs were lost, which marked the largest loss of jobs in the United States in 34 years.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The Bureau of Labor Statistics reported that in the last four months of 2008, 1.9 million jobs were lost.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] By the end of 2008, the U.S. had lost 2.6 million jobs.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] To aid with the situation, Bush signed a $170 billion economic stimulus package which was intended to improve the economic situation by sending tax rebate checks to many Americans and providing tax breaks for struggling businesses.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The Bush administration pushed for significantly increased regulation of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac in 2003, and after two years, the regulations passed the House but died in the Senate.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Many Republican senators, as well as influential members of the Bush Administration, feared that the agency created by these regulations would merely be mimicking the private sector's risky practices.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In September 2008, the 2008 financial crisis intensified, beginning with the Federal takeover of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac followed by the bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers and a federal bailout of American International Group for $85 billion.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Many economists and world governments determined that the situation had become the worst financial crisis since the Great Depression.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Additional regulation over the housing market would have been beneficial, according to former Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush, meanwhile, proposed a financial rescue plan to buy back a large portion of the U.S. mortgage market.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush undertook many educational agendas, such as increasing the funding for the National Science Foundation and National Institutes of Health in his first years of office and creating education programs to strengthen the grounding in science and mathematics for American high school students.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Funding for the NIH was cut in 2006, the first such cut in 36 years, due to rising inflation.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] One of the administration's early major initiatives was the No Child Left Behind Act, which aimed to measure and close the gap between rich and poor student performance, provide options to parents with students in low-performing schools, and target more federal funding to low-income schools.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] This landmark education initiative passed with broad bipartisan support, including the support of Senator Ted Kennedy of Massachusetts.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] It was signed into law by Bush in early 2002.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Many contend that the initiative has been successful, as cited by the fact that students in the U.S. have performed significantly better on state reading and math tests since Bush signed "No Child Left Behind" into law.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Critics argue that it is underfunded and that NCLBA's focus on "high-stakes testing" and quantitative outcomes is counterproductive.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] On November 1, 2005, Bush launched a *National Strategy for Pandemic Influenza*, which culminated in an implementation plan published by the Homeland Security Council in May 2006.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] After being re-elected, Bush signed into law a Medicare drug benefit program which, according to Jan Crawford, resulted in "the greatest expansion in America's welfare state in forty years" – the bill's costs approached $7 trillion.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In 2007, Bush opposed and vetoed State Children's Health Insurance Program (SCHIP) legislation, which was added by the Democrats onto a war funding bill and passed by Congress.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The SCHIP legislation would have significantly expanded federally funded healthcare benefits and plans to children of some low-income families.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] It was to be funded by an increase in the cigarette tax.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush viewed the legislation as a move toward socialized health care, and asserted that the program could benefit families making as much as $83,000 per year who did not need the help.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] On May 21, 2008, Bush signed into law the Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act, aimed to protect Americans against health insurance and employment discrimination based on a person's genetic information.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The issue had been debated for 13 years before it finally became law.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The measure is designed to protect citizens without hindering genetic research.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Following Republican efforts to pass the Medicare Act of 2003, Bush signed the bill, which included major changes to the Medicare program by providing beneficiaries with some assistance in paying for prescription drugs, while relying on private insurance for the delivery of benefits.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The retired persons lobby group AARP worked with the Bush Administration on the program and gave their endorsement.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush said the law, estimated to cost $400 billion over the first ten years, would give the elderly "better choices and more control over their health care".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush began his second term by outlining a major initiative to reform Social Security, which was facing record deficit projections beginning in 2005.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush made it the centerpiece of his domestic agenda despite opposition from some in the U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Democrats opposed the proposal to partially privatize the system.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush embarked on a 60-day national tour, campaigning for his initiative in media events known as "Conversations on Social Security" in an attempt to gain public support.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Nevertheless, public support for the proposal declined, and the House Republican leadership decided not to put Social Security reform on the priority list for the remainder of their 2005 legislative agenda.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The proposal's legislative prospects were further diminished by autumn 2005 due to political fallout from the response to Hurricane Katrina.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] He also cited that the Senate had voted 95–0 in 1997 on a resolution expressing its disapproval of the protocol.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In May 2001, Bush signed an executive order to create an interagency task force to streamline energy projects, and later signed two other executive orders to tackle environmental issues.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In 2002, Bush proposed the Clear Skies Act of 2003, which aimed at amending the Clean Air Act to reduce air pollution through the use of emissions trading programs.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Many experts argued that this legislation would have weakened the original legislation by allowing higher emission rates of pollutants than were previously legal.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The initiative was introduced to Congress, but failed to make it out of committee.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Later in 2006, Bush declared the Northwestern Hawaiian Islands a national monument, creating the largest marine reserve to date.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The Papahānaumokuākea Marine National Monument comprises 84 million acres (340,000 km2) and is home to 7,000 species of fish, birds, and other marine animals, many of which are specific to only those islands.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The move was hailed by conservationists for "its foresight and leadership in protecting this incredible area".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush has said he believes that global warming is real and has noted that it is a serious problem, but he asserted there is a "debate over whether it's man-made or naturally caused".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The Bush Administration's stance on global warming remained controversial in the scientific and environmental communities.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Critics have alleged that the administration misinformed the public and did not do enough to reduce carbon emissions and deter global warming.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In his 2006 State of the Union Address, Bush declared, "America is addicted to oil" and launched his *Advanced Energy Initiative* to increase energy development research.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In his 2007 State of the Union Address, Bush renewed his pledge to work toward diminished reliance on foreign oil by reducing fossil fuel consumption and increasing alternative fuel production.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Amid high gasoline prices in 2008, Bush lifted a ban on offshore drilling.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] However, the move was largely symbolic because there was still a federal law banning offshore drilling.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush said: "This means that the only thing standing between the American people and these vast oil reserves is action from the U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Congress." Bush had said in June 2008, "In the long run, the solution is to reduce demand for oil by promoting alternative energy technologies.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] My administration has worked with Congress to invest in gas-saving technologies like advanced batteries and hydrogen fuel cells ...
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In the short run, the American economy will continue to rely largely on oil.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] And that means we need to increase supply, especially here at home.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Federal funding for medical research involving the creation or destruction of human embryos through the Department of Health and Human Services and the National Institutes of Health has been forbidden by law since the passage of the Dickey–Wicker Amendment in 1995.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush has said he supports adult stem cell research and has supported federal legislation that finances adult stem cell research.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] However, Bush did not support embryonic stem cell research.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] On August 9, 2001, Bush signed an executive order lifting the ban on federal funding for the 71 existing "lines" of stem cells, but the ability of these existing lines to provide an adequate medium for testing has been questioned.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Testing can be done on only 12 of the original lines, and all approved lines have been cultured in contact with mouse cells, creating safety issues that complicate development and approval of therapies from these lines.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] On July 19, 2006, Bush used his veto power for the first time in his presidency to veto the Stem Cell Research Enhancement Act.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The bill would have repealed the Dickey–Wicker Amendment, thereby permitting federal money to be used for research where stem cells are derived from the destruction of an embryo.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Nearly eight million immigrants came to the U.S. from 2000 to 2005, more than in any other five-year period in the nation's history.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In 2006, Bush urged Congress to allow more than twelve million illegal immigrants to work in the United States with the creation of a "temporary guest-worker program".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush also urged Congress to provide additional funds for border security and committed to deploying 6,000 National Guard troops to the Mexico–United States border.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] From May to June 2007, Bush strongly supported the Comprehensive Immigration Reform Act of 2007, which was written by a bipartisan group of senators with the active participation of the Bush administration.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush argued that the lack of legal status denies the protections of U.S. laws to millions of people who face dangers of poverty and exploitation, and penalizes employers despite a demand for immigrant labor.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush contended that the proposed bill did not amount to amnesty.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] A heated public debate followed, which resulted in a substantial rift within the Republican Party, most conservatives opposed it because of its legalization or amnesty provisions.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The bill was eventually defeated in the Senate on June 28, 2007, when a cloture motion failed on a 46–53 vote.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush expressed disappointment upon the defeat of one of his signature domestic initiatives.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The Bush administration later proposed a series of immigration enforcement measures that do not require a change in law.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] On September 19, 2010, former Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert said that Bush offered to accept 100,000 Palestinian refugees as American citizens if a permanent settlement had been reached between Israel and the Palestinian Authority.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Hurricane Katrina struck early in Bush's second term and was one of the most damaging natural disasters in U.S. history.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Katrina formed in late August during the 2005 Atlantic hurricane season and devastated much of the north-central Gulf Coast of the United States, particularly New Orleans.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush declared a state of emergency in Louisiana on August 27 and in Mississippi and Alabama the following day.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The eye of the hurricane made landfall on August 29, and New Orleans began to flood due to levee breaches; later that day, Bush declared a major disaster in Louisiana, officially authorizing FEMA to start using federal funds to assist in the recovery effort.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] On August 30, DHS Secretary Michael Chertoff declared it "an incident of national significance", triggering the first use of the newly created National Response Plan.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Three days later, on September 2, National Guard troops first entered the city of New Orleans.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The same day, Bush toured parts of Louisiana, Mississippi, and Alabama and declared that the success of the recovery effort up to that point was "not enough".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] As the disaster in New Orleans intensified, Bush received widespread criticism for downplaying his administration's role in the inadequate response.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Leaders attacked Bush for having appointed incompetent leaders to positions of power at FEMA, notably Michael D.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Brown; federal resources to respond were also limited as a result of being allocated to the Iraq War, and Bush himself did not act upon warnings of floods.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush responded to mounting criticism by claiming to accept full responsibility for the federal government's failures in its handling of the emergency.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] It has been argued that with Katrina, Bush passed a political tipping point from which he would not recover.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] During Bush's second term, a controversy arose over the Justice Department's midterm dismissal of seven United States Attorneys.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The White House maintained that they were fired for poor performance.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Attorney General Alberto Gonzales later resigned over the issue, along with other senior members of the Justice Department.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The House Judiciary Committee issued subpoenas for advisers Harriet Miers and Josh Bolten to testify regarding this matter, but Bush directed Miers and Bolten not to comply with those subpoenas, invoking his right of executive privilege.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush maintained that all his advisers were covered under a broad executive privilege protection to receive candid advice.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The Justice Department determined that the President's order was legal.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Although congressional investigations focused on whether the Justice Department and the White House were using the U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Attorney positions for political advantage, no official findings have been released.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] On March 10, 2008, the Congress filed a federal lawsuit to enforce their issued subpoenas.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] On July 31, 2008, a United States district court judge ruled that Bush's top advisers were not immune from congressional subpoenas.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In all, twelve Justice Department officials resigned rather than testify under oath before Congress.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] They included Attorney General Alberto Gonzales and his chief of staff Kyle Sampson, Gonzales' liaison to the White House Monica Goodling, aide to the president Karl Rove and his senior aide Sara Taylor.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In addition, legal counsel to the president Harriet Miers and deputy chief of staff to the president Joshua Bolten were both found in contempt of Congress.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In 2010, the Justice Department investigator concluded that though political considerations did play a part in as many as four of the attorney firings, the firings were "inappropriately political" but not criminal.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] According to the prosecutors, there was insufficient evidence to pursue prosecution for any criminal offense.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] During his presidential campaign, Bush's foreign policy platform included support for stronger economic and political relationships with Latin America, especially Mexico, and a reduction of involvement in "nation-building" and other small-scale military engagements.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The administration pursued a national missile defense.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush was an advocate of China's entry into the World Trade Organization.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush began his second term with an emphasis on improving strained relations with European nations.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] He appointed long-time adviser Karen Hughes to oversee a global public relations campaign.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush lauded the pro-democracy struggles in Georgia and Ukraine.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In March 2006, Bush visited India in a trip focused particularly on areas of nuclear energy, counter-terrorism co-operation, and discussions that would eventually lead to the India–United States Civil Nuclear Agreement.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] This was in stark contrast to decades of U.S. policy, such as the stance taken by his predecessor, Bill Clinton, whose approach and response to India after the 1998 nuclear tests has been characterized as "sanctions and hectoring".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Midway through Bush's second term, questions arose whether Bush was retreating from his freedom and democracy agenda, which was highlighted in policy changes toward some oil-rich former Soviet republics in central Asia.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush signed the Strategic Offensive Reductions Treaty with Russia.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] He withdrew U.S. support for several international agreements, including, in 2002, the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty (ABM) with Russia.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] This marked the first time in post-World War II history that the United States had withdrawn from a major international arms treaty.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Russian president Vladimir Putin stated that American withdrawal from the ABM Treaty was a mistake.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush supported Sharon's unilateral disengagement plan, and lauded the democratic elections held in Palestine after Arafat's death.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush also expressed U.S. support for the defense of Taiwan following the stand-off in April 2001 with China over the Hainan Island incident, when an EP-3E Aries II surveillance aircraft collided with a People's Liberation Army Air Force jet, leading to the detention of U.S. personnel.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] From 2003 to 2004, Bush authorized U.S. military intervention in Haiti and Liberia to protect U.S. interests.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush condemned the militia attacks Darfur and denounced the killings in Sudan as genocide.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush said an international peacekeeping presence was critical in Darfur, but he opposed referring the situation to the International Criminal Court.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] On June 10, 2007, Bush met with Albanian Prime Minister Sali Berisha and became the first president to visit Albania.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] He later voiced his support for the independence of Kosovo.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In early 2008, Bush vowed full support for admitting Ukraine and Georgia into NATO despite Russia's opposition to the further enlargement of NATO.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] During the 2008 Russo-Georgian diplomatic crisis, Bush condemned Russia for recognizing the separatist government of South Ossetia.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The September 11 terrorist attacks were a major turning point in Bush's presidency.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] That evening, he addressed the nation from the Oval Office, promising a strong response to the attacks.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] He also emphasized the need for the nation to come together and comfort the families of the victims.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Three days after the attacks, Bush visited Ground Zero and met with then-New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani, firefighters, police officers, and volunteers.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] Bush addressed the gathering via a megaphone while standing on rubble: "I can hear you.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In a September 20 speech, Bush condemned Osama bin Laden and his organization al-Qaeda, and issued an ultimatum to the Taliban regime in Afghanistan, where bin Laden was operating, to "hand over the terrorists, or ... share in their fate".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The Taliban's leader, Mullah Omar, refused to hand over bin Laden.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] The continued presence of U.S. troops in Saudi Arabia after the 1991 Gulf War was one of the stated motivations behind the September 11 attacks.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p02] In 2003, the U.S. withdrew most of its troops from Saudi Arabia.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The Bush Administration asserted both a right and the intention to wage preemptive war, or preventive war.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] This became the basis for the Bush Doctrine, which weakened the unprecedented levels of international and domestic support for the United States that had followed the September 11 attacks.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Dissent and criticism of Bush's leadership in the war on terror increased as the war in Iraq continued.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The Iraq war sparked many protests and riots in different parts of the world.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In 2006, a National Intelligence Estimate concluded that the Iraq War had become the "cause célèbre for jihadists".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On October 7, 2001, U.S. and British forces initiated bombing campaigns that led to the arrival of Northern Alliance troops in Kabul on November 13.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The main goals of the war were to defeat the Taliban, drive al-Qaeda out of Afghanistan, and capture key al-Qaeda leaders.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In December 2001, the Pentagon reported that the Taliban had been defeated, but cautioned that the war would go on to continue weakening Taliban and al-Qaeda leaders.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Later that month the UN had installed the Afghan Transitional Administration chaired by Hamid Karzai.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Efforts to kill or capture al-Qaeda leader Osama bin Laden failed as he escaped a battle in December 2001 in the mountainous region of Tora Bora, which the Bush Administration later acknowledged to have resulted from a failure to commit enough U.S. ground troops.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] It was not until May 2011, two years after Bush left office, that Bin Laden was killed by U.S. forces under the Obama administration.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Despite the initial success in driving the Taliban from power in Kabul, by early 2003 the Taliban was regrouping, amassing new funds and recruits.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The 2005 failure of Operation Red Wings showed that the Taliban had returned.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In 2006, the Taliban insurgency appeared larger, fiercer and better organized than expected, with large-scale allied offensives such as Operation Mountain Thrust attaining limited success.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] As a result, Bush commissioned 3,500 additional troops to the country in March 2007.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Beginning with his January 29, 2002 State of the Union address, Bush began publicly focusing attention on Iraq, which he labeled as part of an "axis of evil" allied with terrorists and posing "a grave and growing danger" to U.S. interests through possession of weapons of mass destruction.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In the latter half of 2002, CIA reports contained assertions of Saddam Hussein's intent of reconstituting nuclear weapons programs, not properly accounting for Iraqi biological and chemical weapons, and that some Iraqi missiles had a range greater than allowed by the UN sanctions.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Contentions that the Bush Administration manipulated or exaggerated the threat and evidence of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction capabilities would eventually become a major point of criticism for the president.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In late 2002 and early 2003, Bush urged the United Nations to enforce Iraqi disarmament mandates, precipitating a diplomatic crisis.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In November 2002, Hans Blix and Mohamed ElBaradei led UN weapons inspectors in Iraq, but were advised by the U.S. to depart the country four days prior to the U.S. invasion, despite their requests for more time to complete their tasks.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The U.S. initially sought a UN Security Council resolution authorizing the use of military force but dropped the bid for UN approval due to vigorous opposition from several countries.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The Bush administration's claim that the Iraq War was part of the war on terror had been questioned and contested by political analysts.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] More than 20 nations (most notably the United Kingdom) designated the "coalition of the willing" joined the United States in invading Iraq.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] They launched the invasion on March 20, 2003.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The Iraqi military was quickly defeated.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The capital, Baghdad, fell on April 9, 2003.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On May 1, Bush declared the end of major combat operations in Iraq.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The initial success of U.S. operations increased his popularity, but the U.S. and allied forces faced a growing insurgency led by sectarian groups; Bush's "Mission Accomplished" speech was later criticized as premature.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] From 2004 until 2007, the situation in Iraq deteriorated further, with some observers arguing that there was a full-scale civil war in Iraq.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush's policies met with criticism, including demands domestically to set a timetable to withdraw troops from Iraq.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The 2006 report of the bipartisan Iraq Study Group, led by James Baker, concluded that the situation in Iraq was "grave and deteriorating".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] While Bush admitted there were strategic mistakes made in regard to the stability of Iraq, he maintained he would not change the overall Iraq strategy.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] According to Iraq Body Count, some 251,000 Iraqis have been killed in the civil war following the U.S.-led invasion, including at least 163,841 civilians.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In January 2005, elections recognized by the West as free and fair were held in Iraq for the first time in 50 years.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] This led to the election of Jalal Talabani as president and Nouri al-Maliki as Prime Minister of Iraq.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] A referendum to approve a constitution in Iraq was held in October 2005, supported by most Shiites and many Kurds.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On January 10, 2007, Bush launched a surge of 21,500 more troops for Iraq, as well as a job program for Iraqis, more reconstruction proposals, and $1.2 billion (equivalent to $1.9 billion in 2025) for these programs.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On May 1, 2007, Bush used his second-ever veto to reject a bill setting a deadline for the withdrawal of U.S. troops, saying the debate over the conflict was "understandable" but insisting that a continued U.S. presence there was crucial.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In March 2008, Bush praised the Iraqi government's "bold decision" to launch the Battle of Basra against the Mahdi Army, calling it "a defining moment in the history of a free Iraq".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He said he would carefully weigh recommendations from his commanding General David Petraeus and Ambassador Ryan Crocker about how to proceed after the end of the military buildup in the summer of 2008.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He also praised the Iraqis' legislative achievements, including a pension law, a revised de-Baathification law, a new budget, an amnesty law, and a provincial powers measure that, he said, set the stage for the Iraqi elections.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] By July 2008, American troop deaths had reached their lowest number since the war began, and due to increased stability in Iraq, Bush withdrew of additional American forces.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] During Bush's last visit to Iraq in December 2008, Iraqi journalist Muntadhar al-Zaidi threw both of his shoes at him during an official press conference with Iraqi Prime Minister Nouri al-Maliki.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Al-Zaidi yelled that the shoes were a "farewell kiss" and "for the widows and orphans and all those killed in Iraq".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In March 2010, Center for Public Integrity released a report that President Bush's administration had made more than 900 false pretenses in a two-year period about the alleged threat of Iraq against the United States, as his rationale to engage in war in Iraq.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Following the terrorist attacks of September 11, Bush issued an executive order that authorized the President's Surveillance Program.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The new directive allowed the National Security Agency to monitor communications between suspected terrorists outside the U.S. and parties within the U.S. without obtaining a warrant, which previously had been required by the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] As of 2009, the other provisions of the program remained highly classified.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The program proved to be controversial; critics of the administration and organizations such as the American Bar Association argued that it was illegal.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In August 2006, a U.S. district court judge ruled that the NSA electronic surveillance program was unconstitutional, but on July 6, 2007, the ruling was vacated by the United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit on the grounds that the plaintiffs lacked standing.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On January 17, 2007, Attorney General Alberto Gonzales informed U.S.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Senate leaders that the program would not be reauthorized by the President, but would be subjected to judicial oversight.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Later in 2007, the NSA launched a replacement for the program, referred to as PRISM, which was subject to the oversight of the United States Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] This program was not publicly revealed until reports by *The Washington Post* and *The Guardian* emerged in June 2013.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush authorized the CIA to use waterboarding and several other "enhanced interrogation techniques" that several critics, including Barack Obama, would label as torture.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The CIA had exercised the technique on certain key terrorist suspects under authority given to it in the Bybee Memo from the Attorney General, though the memo was later withdrawn.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Army Field Manuals which assert "that harsh interrogation tactics elicit unreliable information", the Bush administration believed these enhanced interrogations "provided critical information" to preserve American lives.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On October 17, 2006, Bush signed the Military Commissions Act of 2006 into law.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The new rule was enacted in the wake of the Supreme Court's decision in *Hamdan v.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] 557 (2006), which allowed the U.S. government to prosecute unlawful enemy combatants by military commission rather than a standard trial.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The law also denied the detainees access to *habeas corpus* and barred the torture of prisoners.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The provision of the law allowed the president to determine what constitutes "torture".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In April 2009, the ACLU sued and won release of the secret memos that had authorized the Bush administration's interrogation tactics.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] One memo detailed specific interrogation tactics including a footnote which described waterboarding as torture and stating that the form of waterboarding used by the CIA was far more intense than authorized by the Justice Department.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush publicly condemned Kim Jong-il of North Korea and identified North Korea as one of three states in an "axis of evil".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On May 7, 2007, North Korea agreed to shut down its nuclear reactors immediately pending the release of frozen funds held in a foreign bank account.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] This was a result of a series of three-way talks initiated by the United States and including China.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On September 2, 2007, North Korea agreed to disclose and dismantle all its nuclear programs by the end of 2007.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] By May 2009, North Korea had restarted its nuclear program and threatened to attack South Korea.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On June 22, 2010, Bush said: "While South Korea prospers, the people of North Korea have suffered profoundly," adding that communism had resulted in dire poverty, mass starvation, and brutal suppression.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush expanded economic sanctions on Syria.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In 2003, Bush signed the Syria Accountability Act, which expanded sanctions on Syria.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In early 2007, the Treasury Department, acting on a June 2005 executive order, froze American bank accounts of Syria's Higher Institute of Applied Science and Technology, Electronics Institute, and National Standards and Calibration Laboratory.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush's order prohibits Americans from doing business with these institutions suspected of helping spread weapons of mass destruction and being supportive of terrorism.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Under separate executive orders signed by Bush in 2004 and later 2007, the Treasury Department froze the assets of two Lebanese and two Syrians, accusing them of activities to "undermine the legitimate political process in Lebanon" in November 2007.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In the State of the Union address in January 2003, Bush outlined a five-year strategy for global emergency AIDS relief, the President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR).
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush announced $15 billion for this effort, which directly supported life-saving antiretroviral treatment for more than 3.2 million men, women and children worldwide.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The U.S. government had spent some $44 billion on the project since 2003 (a figure which includes $7 billion contributed to the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis, and Malaria, a multilateral organization), which saved an estimated five million lives by 2013.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On February 7, 2001, while Bush was in the residence area of the White House, Robert W.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Pickett, standing outside the perimeter fence, discharged a number of shots from a Taurus .38 Special revolver "in the general direction" of the White House.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Furthermore, he was initially charged with discharging a firearm during a crime, carrying a 10-year mandatory sentence, but following a plea agreement, Pickett instead entered a guilty plea to a firearms violation and an Alford plea to assaulting a federal officer.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He was sentenced to three years at the Federal Medical Center, Rochester followed by three years of probation.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On May 10, 2005, while President Bush was giving a speech in Freedom Square, Vladimir Arutyunian, a native Georgian who was born to a family of ethnic Armenians, threw a live Soviet-made RGD-5 hand grenade toward the podium.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] It landed in the crowd about 61 feet (19 m) from the podium after hitting a girl, but it did not detonate because a red tartan handkerchief was wrapped tightly around it, preventing the safety lever from detaching.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Georgian president Mikheil Saakashvili was seated nearby.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] After escaping that day, Arutyunian was arrested in July 2005.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] During his arrest, he killed an Interior Ministry agent.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He was convicted in January 2006 and given a life sentence.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On December 14, 2008, Muntadhar al-Zaidi, an Iraqi journalist, threw both of his shoes at Bush during a press conference in Baghdad.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush was not injured, having ducked the pair of shoes.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] However, White House press secretary Dana Perino received a bruise on her face after being hit by a microphone boom knocked over by security.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Al-Zaidi received a three-year prison sentence which was reduced to one year.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On September 15, 2009, he was released early for good behavior.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He was confirmed by the Senate on September 29, 2005.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On October 3, 2005, Bush nominated White House Counsel Harriet Miers to succeed O'Connor; however, Miers withdrew her nomination on October 27 after encountering significant opposition from both parties, who found her to be ill-prepared and uninformed on the law.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Finally, on October 31, Bush nominated federal appellate judge Samuel Alito, who was confirmed by the Senate to replace O'Connor on January 31, 2006.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In addition to his two Supreme Court appointments, Bush appointed 62 judges to the United States courts of appeals and 261 judges to the United States district courts.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush's upbringing in West Texas, his accent, his vacations to his Texas ranch, and his penchant for country metaphors contribute to his folksy, American cowboy image.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] "I think people look at him and think John Wayne", said Piers Morgan, editor of the British *Daily Mirror*.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush has been parodied by the media, comedians, and other politicians.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Detractors tended to cite linguistic errors made by Bush during his public speeches, which are colloquially referred to as Bushisms.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In contrast to his father, who was perceived as having troubles with an overarching unifying theme, Bush embraced larger visions and was seen as a man of larger ideas and associated huge risks.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Tony Blair wrote in 2010 that the caricature of Bush as being dumb is "ludicrous" and that Bush is "very smart".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In an interview with *Playboy*, *The New York Times* columnist David Brooks said Bush "was 60 IQ points smarter in private than he was in public.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush began his presidency with approval ratings near 60 percent.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] After the September 11 attacks, Bush gained an approval rating of 90 percent, maintaining 80–90 percent approval for four months after the attacks.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] It remained over 50 percent during most of his first term and then fell to as low as 19 percent in his second term.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In 2000 and again in 2004, *Time* magazine named George W.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush as its Person of the Year, a title awarded to someone who the editors believe "has done the most to influence the events of the year".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In May 2004, Gallup reported that 89 percent of the Republican electorate approved of Bush.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] However, the support waned due mostly to a minority of Republicans' frustration with him on issues of spending, illegal immigration, and Middle Eastern affairs.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Within the United States armed forces, according to an unscientific survey, the president was strongly supported in the 2004 presidential elections.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] While 73 percent of military personnel said they would vote for Bush, 18 percent preferred his Democratic rival, John Kerry.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] According to Peter Feaver, a Duke University political scientist who has studied the political leanings of the U.S. military, members of the armed services supported Bush because they found him more likely than Kerry to complete the War in Iraq.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush's approval rating surged to 74 percent at the beginning of the Iraq War, up 19 points from his pre-war rating of 55 percent.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush's approval rating went below the 50 percent mark in AP-Ipsos polling in December 2004.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Thereafter, his approval ratings and approval of his handling of domestic and foreign policy issues steadily dropped.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Amid this criticism, the Democratic Party regained control of Congress in the 2006 midterm elections.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Polls conducted in 2006 showed an average of 37 percent approval ratings for Bush, the lowest for any second-term president at that point in his term since Harry S.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Truman in March 1951 (when Truman's approval rating was 28 percent), which contributed to what Bush called the "thumping" of the Republican Party in the 2006 elections.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Throughout most of 2007, Bush's approval rating hovered in the mid-thirties; the average for his entire second term was 37 percent, according to Gallup.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] By the beginning of 2008, his final year in office, Bush's approval rating had dropped to a low of just 19 percent, largely from the loss of support among Republicans.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Commenting on his low poll numbers and accusations of being "the worst president", Bush would say, "I make decisions on what I think is right for the United States based upon principles.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] There were calls for Bush's impeachment, though most polls showed a plurality of Americans would not support such an action.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The arguments offered for impeachment usually centered on the NSA warrantless surveillance controversy, the Bush administration's justification for the war in Iraq, and alleged violations of the Geneva Conventions.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Representative Dennis Kucinich (D-OH), who had run against Bush during the 2004 presidential campaign, introduced 35 articles of impeachment on the floor of the House of Representatives against Bush on June 9, 2008, but Speaker Nancy Pelosi (D-CA) declared that impeachment was "off the table".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In polls conducted in the fall, just before the 2008 election, his approval ratings remained at record lows of 19 to 20 percent, while his disapproval ratings ranged from 67 percent to as high as 75 percent.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In polling conducted January 9–11, 2009, his final job approval rating by Gallup was 34 percent, which placed him on par with Jimmy Carter and Harry S.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Truman, the other presidents whose final Gallup ratings measured in the low 30s (Richard Nixon's final Gallup approval rating was even lower, at 24 percent).
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] According to a CBS News/*New York Times* poll conducted January 11–15, 2009, Bush's final approval rating in office was 22 percent, the lowest in American history.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush was criticized internationally and targeted by the global anti-war and anti-globalization movements for his administration's foreign policy.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Views of him within the international community – even in France, a close ally of the United States – were more negative than those of most previous American presidents.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush was described as having especially close personal relationships with Tony Blair of the United Kingdom and Vicente Fox of Mexico, although formal relations were sometimes strained.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Other leaders, such as Hamid Karzai of Afghanistan, Yoweri Museveni of Uganda, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero of Spain, and Hugo Chávez of Venezuela, openly criticized the president.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Later in Bush's presidency, tensions arose between him and Vladimir Putin, which led to a cooling of their relationship.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In 2006, most respondents in 18 of 21 countries surveyed around the world were found to hold an unfavorable opinion of Bush.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Respondents indicated that they judged his administration as negative for world security.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In 2007, the Pew Global Attitudes Project reported that during the Bush presidency, attitudes towards the United States, and towards Americans, became less favorable around the world.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The Pew Research Center's 2007 Global Attitudes poll found that in only nine countries of 47 did most respondents express "a lot of confidence" or "some confidence" in Bush: Ethiopia, Ghana, India, Israel, Ivory Coast, Kenya, Mali, Nigeria, and Uganda.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] A March 2007 survey of public opinion in six Arab nations conducted by Zogby International and the University of Maryland found that Bush was the most disliked world leader.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] During a June 2007 visit to the predominantly Muslim Albania, Bush was greeted enthusiastically.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Albania has a population of 2.8 million, has troops in both Iraq and Afghanistan, and the country's government is highly supportive of American foreign policy.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] A huge image of the President was hung in the middle of the capital city of Tirana flanked by Albanian and American flags while a local street was named after him.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] A shirt-sleeved statue of Bush was unveiled in Fushë-Krujë, a few kilometers northwest of Tirana.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The Bush administration's support for the unilateral declaration of independence of Albanian-majority Kosovo, while endearing him to the Albanians, troubled U.S. relations with Serbia, leading to the February 2008 torching of the U.S. embassy in Belgrade.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] After the inauguration of Barack Obama, Bush and his family flew from Andrews Air Force Base to a homecoming celebration in Midland, Texas, and then returned to their ranch in Crawford, Texas.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] They bought a home in the Preston Hollow neighborhood of Dallas where they live.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He also attended every home playoff game during the Rangers' 2010 season and, accompanied by his father, threw out the ceremonial first pitch at the Rangers Ballpark in Arlington for Game 4 of the 2010 World Series on October 31.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He also threw the first pitch in Game 1 of the 2023 World Series.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On August 6, 2013, Bush was successfully treated for a coronary artery blockage with a stent.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The blockage had been found during an annual medical examination.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In reaction to the 2016 shooting of Dallas police officers, Bush said: "Laura and I are heartbroken by the heinous acts of violence in our city last night.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Since leaving office, Bush has kept a relatively low profile.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush has spoken in favor of increased global participation of women in politics and societal matters in foreign countries.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In March 2009, he delivered his first post-presidency speech in Calgary, Alberta, appeared via video on *The Colbert Report* during which he praised U.S. troops for earning a "special place in American history", and attended the funeral of Senator Ted Kennedy.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush made his debut as a motivational speaker on October 26 at the "Get Motivated" seminar in Dallas.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In the aftermath of the Fort Hood shooting on November 5, 2009, the Bushes paid an undisclosed visit to the survivors and the victims' families the day following the shooting, having contacted the base commander requesting that the visit be private and not involve press coverage.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush released his memoirs, *Decision Points*, on November 9, 2010.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] During a pre-release appearance promoting the book, Bush said he considered his biggest accomplishment to be keeping "the country safe amid a real danger", and his greatest failure to be his inability to secure the passage of Social Security reform.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In 2012, he wrote the foreword of *The 4% Solution: Unleashing the Economic Growth America Needs*, an economics book published by the George W.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He also presented the book at the Parkland Memorial Hospital in Dallas, Texas.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush did not physically appear in that year's Republican National Convention (where Mitt Romney obtained the party's nomination for president), instead appearing in a videotape, in which he –alongside his father and immediate family– explains his motives to support Romney.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush appeared on NBC's *The Tonight Show with Jay Leno* on November 19, 2013, along with his wife Laura.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In December, Bush travelled with President Obama to the memorial service of South African president and civil rights leader Nelson Mandela.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] There, they joined former presidents Bill Clinton and Jimmy Carter.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Alongside the 2014 United States–Africa Leaders Summit, Bush, Michelle Obama, the State Department, and the George W.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush Institute hosted a daylong forum on education and health with the spouses of the African leaders attending the summit.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush urged African leaders to avoid discriminatory laws that make the treatment of HIV/AIDS more difficult.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On November 2, Bush spoke at an event to 200 business and civic leaders at the George W.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush Presidential Library and Museum to raise awareness for the upcoming Museum of the Bible in Washington D.C.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On November 11, Bush published a biography of his father titled *41: A Portrait of My Father*.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In an interview published by *Israel Hayom* magazine on June 12, 2015, Bush said that "boots on the ground" would be needed to defeat the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIS).
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He added that people had said during his presidency that he should withdraw American troops from Iraq, but he chose the opposite, sending 30,000 more troops to defeat Al Qaeda in Iraq, and that they indeed were defeated.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush was also asked about Iran but declined to answer, stating that any answer he gives would be interpreted as undermining Obama.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] During the early stages of the 2016 Republican presidential primaries, Bush spoke and campaigned for his brother Jeb Bush at a South Carolina rally.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] However, the party's nomination eventually went to Donald Trump, whom Bush refused to endorse.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Furthermore, he did not attend the party's convention.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] After the 2016 elections, Bush, his father, and his brother Jeb called Trump on the phone to congratulate him on his victory.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On January 20, 2017, Bush and his wife attended Trump's first inauguration.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Images of Bush struggling to put on a rain poncho during the ceremony became an internet meme.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] While leaving the event, Bush allegedly described the ceremony, and Trump's inaugural address in particular, as "some weird shit".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In February 2017, Bush released a book of his own portraits of veterans called *Portraits of Courage*.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In August, following the white nationalist Unite the Right rally, Bush and his father released a joint statement condemning the violence and ideologies present there.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Subsequently, Bush gave a speech in New York where he noted of the current political climate, "Bigotry seems emboldened.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The speech was widely interpreted as a denouncement of Donald Trump and his ideologies, despite Bush not mentioning Trump by name.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On September 1, 2018, Bush and his wife attended the funeral of John McCain at the Washington National Cathedral in Washington, D.C. where Bush delivered remarks at the service.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On November 30, his father died at his home.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Shortly before his death, Bush was able to talk with his father on the phone; his father responded with what would be his last words, "I love you too".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush attended his father's funeral on December 5, delivering a eulogy.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In May 2019 on the tenth anniversary of former South Korean president Roh Moo-hyun's death, Bush visited South Korea to pay respects to Roh, delivering a short eulogy.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On June 1, 2020, Bush released a statement addressing the murder of George Floyd and the subsequent nationwide reaction and protests.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In the statement, Bush wrote that he and former first lady Laura Bush "are anguished by the brutal suffocation of George Floyd and disturbed by the injustice and fear that suffocate our country".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He also elaborated on the racial injustices perpetrated by the police, saying that "it is time for America to examine our tragic failures" and adding "Many doubt the justice of our country, and with good reason.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Black people see the repeated violation of their rights without an urgent and adequate response from American institutions".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On July 30, Bush and his wife, along with former presidents Bill Clinton and Barack Obama, attended and spoke at the funeral for civil rights leader and congressman John Lewis at Ebenezer Baptist Church in Atlanta.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush did not give any endorsements during the 2020 presidential election, but held a virtual fundraiser for U.S. senators Susan Collins (R-ME), Cory Gardner (R-CO), Martha McSally (R-AZ), and Thom Tillis (R-NC).
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] All four were up for reelection and were struggling in the polls.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He also did not attend the 2020 Republican National Convention where President Trump was re-nominated.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In April 2021, Bush told *People* magazine that he did not vote for either Trump or Joe Biden in the general election.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Instead, he wrote in Condoleezza Rice, who served as his national security advisor from 2001 to 2005 and as his secretary of state from 2005 to 2009.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] When the election was called for Biden, Bush congratulated him and his running mate Kamala Harris.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He also congratulated Trump and his supporters "on a hard-fought campaign".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush's outreach to Biden was notable since Republican candidate Donald Trump had not yet conceded.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He also echoed president-elect Biden's message saying that what occurred at the capitol was an "insurrection".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On January 20, Bush and his wife attended Biden's inauguration.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush opposed President Biden's withdrawal of American troops from Afghanistan, saying that the withdrawal made him "concerned" and that it had the potential to "create a vacuum, and into that vacuum is likely to come people who treat women as second class citizens".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] During an interview with Deutsche Welle on July 14, 2021, Bush reaffirmed his opposition to the troop withdrawal, calling the plan "a mistake".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On September 11, 2021, the 20th anniversary of the September 11 attacks, Bush gave a speech at the Flight 93 National Memorial, praising the heroism of the people on Flight 93 and the spirit of America.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He also said that he "saw millions of people instinctively grab for a neighbor's hand and rally to the cause of one another.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush condemned the assassination attempt on then-former president Trump, who was the presumptive Republican nominee, on July 13, 2024, calling it "cowardly" and applauded the Secret Service's response.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] However, Bush did not participate in that year's Republican National Convention, which took place two days after the attempt, and where Trump was nominated for a third time.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He also chose not to endorse any candidate in the presidential election.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] After the election was called for Trump, Bush offered his congratulations to him and his running mate JD Vance.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He stated that the large turnout for the election was a "sign of the health of our republic and the strength of our democratic institutions".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He also congratulated Biden and Harris on their years of public office.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On January 20, 2025, Bush and his wife attended Trump's second inauguration.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On September 10, 2025, Bush released a statement condemning the assassination of Charlie Kirk.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He wrote "Today, a young man was murdered in cold blood while expressing his political views.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] It happened on a college campus, where the open exchange of opposing ideas should be sacrosanct." He also elaborated on political violence in the United States: "Violence and vitriol must be purged from the public square.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Members of other political parties are not our enemies; they are our fellow citizens.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] After Peyton Manning tried to get Bush to appear on *Monday Night Football with Peyton and Eli* for five years, Bush relented.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On the show on November 17, 2025, Bush said that he grew up a Houston Astros and a Houston Oilers fan watching Earl Campbell and Dan Pastorini (he called Pastorini, Dante Pastorini) play for the Oilers.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush also mentioned Billy "White Shoes" Johnson.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush said that he and his group bought the Texas Rangers and he moved to Dallas the same year that Jerry Jones bought the Dallas Cowboys.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] At that time, Bush got to know Jones well and switched his allegiance to the Cowboys.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush mentioned that his father liked the Houston Texans and the Astros, calling him a loyal Houston guy.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush if he thought that he would have a job in public service, Bush answered no and that he would have behaved a lot better in college if he had known.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush talked about growing up in Midland, Texas.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He said you either picked art or football.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] "I chose football." He has run marathons.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On November 20, 2025, Bush and his wife attended the funeral of his former vice president Cheney at the Washington National Cathedral in Washington, D.C., where Bush spoke.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush and his wife attended the dedication ceremony of the Barack Obama Presidential Center on June 18, 2026.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In January 2010, at President Obama's request, Bush and Bill Clinton established the Clinton Bush Haiti Fund to raise contributions for relief and recovery efforts after the 2010 Haiti earthquake earlier that month.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On May 2, 2011, President Obama called Bush, who was at a restaurant with his wife, to inform him that Osama bin Laden had been killed.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The Bushes joined the Obamas in New York City to mark the tenth anniversary of the September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] At the Ground Zero memorial, Bush read a letter that President Abraham Lincoln wrote to a widow who had lost five sons during the Civil War.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] On September 7, 2017, Bush partnered with former presidents Jimmy Carter, George H.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Bush, Bill Clinton, and Barack Obama to work with One America Appeal to help the victims of Hurricane Harvey and Hurricane Irma in the Gulf Coast and Texas communities.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Over the years, President Bush has had a good-natured friendship with Michelle Obama.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] "President Bush and I, we are forever seatmates because of protocol, and that's how we sit at all the official functions," Obama told the *Today Show*.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] "He's my partner in crime at every major thing where all the 'formers' gather.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] So we're together all the time." Bush famously passed mints to Obama during the McCain funeral in September 2018 and gave them to her again during the funeral of his father in December 2018.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] After serving as president, Bush began painting as a hobby after reading Winston Churchill's essay "Painting as a Pastime".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] Subjects have included people, dogs, and still life.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] He has also painted self-portraits and portraits of world leaders, including Vladimir Putin and Tony Blair.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In February 2017, Bush released a book of portraits of veterans, *Portraits of Courage*.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] The net proceeds from his book are donated to the George W.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p03] In May 2019, on the tenth anniversary of former South Korean president Roh Moo-hyun's death, George Bush drew a portrait of Roh to give to his family.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Bush's legacy continues to develop, as time passing allows the development of a more nuanced historical perspective.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Supporters credit his counterterrorism policies with preventing another major terrorist attack from occurring in the U.S. after the September 11 attacks and also praise individual policies such as the Medicare prescription drug benefit and the AIDS relief program known as PEPFAR.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Critics often point to his handling of the Iraq War, specifically the failure to find weapons of mass destruction after claiming they were in Iraq, as well as Bush's handling of tax policy, Hurricane Katrina, climate change and the 2008 financial crisis, as proof that he was unfit to be president.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Ben Ferencz, former chief prosecutor for the United States Army at the Nuremberg Trials, stated that Bush likely committed war crimes in relation to the Iraq War.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Several historians and commentators hold that Bush was one of the most consequential presidents in American history.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Princeton University scholar Julian Zelizer described Bush's presidency as a "transformative" one, and said that "some people hate him, some people love him, but I do think he'll have a much more substantive perception as time goes on".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Bryon Williams of *The Huffington Post* referred to Bush as "the most noteworthy president since FDR" and said the Patriot Act "increased authority of the executive branch at the expense of judicial opinions about when searches and seizures are reasonable" as evidence.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Bush's administration presided over the largest tax cuts since the presidency of Ronald Reagan, and his homeland security reforms proved to be the most significant expansion of the federal government since the Great Society.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Some scholars have situated Bush's presidency as the extension of the Reagan era into the 21st century and the consolidation of American neoconservatism.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Bush has been widely portrayed in film and television, both during and after his presidency.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] He has had various nicknames including "Dubya", "GWB" and "Shrub".
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Bush presidency has been ranked as below-average in surveys of presidential scholars published in the late 2000s and 2010s.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] A 2010 Siena Research Institute survey of the opinions of historians, political scientists, and presidential scholars ranked him 39th out of 43 presidents.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] The survey respondents gave President Bush low ratings on his handling of the U.S. economy, communication, ability to compromise, foreign policy accomplishments, and intelligence.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Bush said in 2013, "Ultimately history will judge the decisions I made, and I won't be around because it will take time for the objective historians to show up.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] I did what I did." C-SPAN's 2021 survey of historians ranked Bush as the 29th-best president; Bush had initially been ranked the 36th in 2009.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Among the public, his reputation has improved in the United States since his presidency ended in 2009.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] In February 2012, Gallup reported that "Americans still rate George W.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] A poll conducted in June 2013 marked the first time recorded by Gallup where his ratings have been more positive than negative, with 49 percent viewing him favorably compared to 46 percent unfavorably.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Other pollsters have noted similar trends of slight improvement in Bush's personal favorability since the end of his presidency.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] In April 2013, Bush's approval rating stood at 47 percent approval and 50 percent disapproval in a poll jointly conducted for *The Washington Post* and ABC, his highest approval rating since December 2005.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Bush had achieved notable gains among seniors, non-college whites, and moderate and conservative Democrats since leaving office, although majorities disapproved of his handling of the economy (53 percent) and the Iraq War (57 percent).
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] His 47 percent approval rating was equal to President Obama's in the same polling period.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] A CNN poll conducted that same month found that 55 percent of Americans said Bush's presidency had been a failure, with opinions divided along party lines, and 43 percent of independents calling it a success.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Bush's public image saw greater improvement in 2017, with a YouGov survey showing 51 percent of favorability from Democrats.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] A 2018 CNN poll subsequently found that 61 percent of respondents held a favorable view of Bush, an increase of nine points from 2015.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] The improvement has been interpreted as Democrats viewing him more favorably in response to Donald Trump's first presidency, an assessment that has also been expressed by Bush himself.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] A street in Tirana, Albania, located directly outside the Albanian Parliament and formerly known as *Rruga Punëtorët e Rilindjes*, was renamed after Bush a few days before he made the first-ever visit by an American president to Albania in June 2007.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] In 2012, Estonian president Toomas Hendrik Ilves awarded Bush the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana for his work in expanding NATO.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Two elementary schools are named after him: one in Stockton Unified School District in Stockton, California, and one in Wylie Independent School District in St.
[src:george-w-bush/george-w-bush-p04] Paul, Texas, in the Dallas-Fort Worth area.
